"""
mkt-christ commentary — Psalms 107–110
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-psalms-107-110.py

Key NT connections:
  Ps107:9  → Luke 1:53 (direct — Magnificat quotes "fills the hungry with good things")
  Ps107:20 → John 1:14 (direct — God sent his word and healed = Word made flesh)
  Ps107:29 → Mark 4:39 (direct — he made the storm be still)
  Ps108:3  → Rom 15:9 (direct — Paul's Gentile-praise catena)
  Ps109:8  → Acts 1:20 (direct — Peter quotes re. replacing Judas)
  Ps109:25 → Matt 27:39 (direct — they wagged their heads at the cross)
  Ps110:1  → already present (most-cited OT verse in NT)
  Ps110:4  → already present (Heb 5:6; 7:17 — Melchizedek priesthood)
  Ps110:2,5-7 — Christ's rule and final judgment
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}


def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


NEW_DATA = {
  "107": {
    "1": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>Oh give thanks to the LORD, for he is good, for his steadfast love endures forever!</em> The everlasting steadfast love — the theme of John 3:16 and Rom 8:38-39. The church's Eucharist (Greek: thanksgiving) is the fulfillment of this \"give thanks\" — Christ institutes the meal of perpetual thanksgiving at the Last Supper, directing the church to remember and proclaim his love until he comes (1 Cor 11:26).</p>",
    "2": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Let the redeemed of the LORD say so, whom he has redeemed from trouble</em> The redeemed testifying to redemption — the vocation of the church. Rev 5:9: the four living creatures and elders sing to the Lamb, <em>for you were slain, and by your blood you ransomed people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation.</em> The redeemed of the LORD say so by singing the Lamb's praise in every tongue.</p>",
    "3": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>and gathered in from the lands, from the east and from the west, from the north and from the south.</em> Gathering from all directions — the eschatological ingathering Christ announces: <em>people will come from east and west, and from north and south, and recline at table in the kingdom of God</em> (Luke 13:29). Matt 24:31: <em>he will send out his angels... and they will gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of heaven to the other.</em></p>",
    "4": "<p><span class=\"level\">type</span> <em>Some wandered in desert wastes, finding no way to a city to dwell in;</em> Wandering without a city — the condition of fallen humanity: <em>strangers and exiles on the earth</em> seeking a city (Heb 11:13-14). Christ brings the wanderers to the heavenly city: <em>for he has prepared for them a city</em> (Heb 11:16). The New Jerusalem descends from heaven (Rev 21:2) — the city the desert-wanderers have been seeking.</p>",
    "5": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>hungry and thirsty, their soul fainted within them.</em> Hunger and thirst unto fainting — the destitution Christ addresses: <em>Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied</em> (Matt 5:6). The hunger of v5 is the condition Christ pronounces blessed because he is the bread and water that satisfies: <em>whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst</em> (John 6:35).</p>",
    "6": "<p><span class=\"level\">type</span> <em>Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress.</em> Crying and receiving deliverance — the pattern fulfilled in Christ's cry from the cross (Matt 27:46) and answered by resurrection (Heb 5:7: <em>he offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverence</em>). Christ cries out and is delivered; those who cry in his name receive the same answer.</p>",
    "7": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He led them by a straight way till they reached a city to dwell in.</em> The straight way to the city — Christ: <em>I am the way, and the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me</em> (John 14:6). The straight way to the heavenly city is not a road but a person; he both leads and is the path. The wanderers of v4 find the city only through the one who is the way.</p>",
    "8": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!</em> The refrain (repeated in v15, v21, v31) — the response of wonder and thanks to God's redemptive acts. The supreme wondrous work is the resurrection: <em>This is the Lord's doing; it is marvelous in our eyes</em> (Ps 118:23, quoted at Matt 21:42). The four-fold refrain of Ps 107 finds its ultimate object in the once-for-all work of Christ.</p>",
    "9": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>for he satisfies the longing soul, and the hungry soul he fills with good things.</em> Luke 1:53 quotes this in the Magnificat: <em>he has filled the hungry with good things.</em> Mary sings the fulfillment of Ps 107:9 in the Incarnation — God satisfying the longing soul by giving his Son. Christ: <em>I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst</em> (John 6:35).</p>",
    "10": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Some sat in darkness and in the shadow of death, prisoners in affliction and in irons,</em> Darkness and shadow of death — Isa 9:2 (quoted in Matt 4:16): <em>the people dwelling in darkness have seen a great light, and for those dwelling in the region and shadow of death, on them a light has dawned.</em> Christ is the light entering the darkness of v10. The prisoners in irons are those to whom he proclaims liberty (Luke 4:18; Isa 61:1).</p>",
    "11": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>for they had rebelled against the words of God, and spurned the counsel of the Most High.</em> Rebellion against God's word as the root of bondage — the human condition Christ addresses at its source. He does not merely release prisoners; he deals with why they are prisoners. He himself is the Word made flesh (John 1:14) — the one they rejected — and his cross deals with the guilt of that rejection at its root.</p>",
    "12": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>So he bowed their heart down with hard labor; they fell down, with none to help.</em> No helper when the heart bows down — the Good Samaritan parable enacted: Christ sees the one fallen with no helper and comes to help (Luke 10:33-35). He came when there was no one to help (Ps 22:11): <em>while we were still weak, at the right time Christ died for the ungodly</em> (Rom 5:6).</p>",
    "13": "<p><span class=\"level\">type</span> <em>Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress.</em> The second rescue refrain — the pattern of cry-and-deliverance Christ permanently fulfills. Heb 5:7: Christ offered up prayers with loud cries and tears and was heard. His rescue from the tomb is the archetypal deliverance from ultimate distress, the pattern for all who cry to him in their trouble.</p>",
    "14": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He brought them out of darkness and the shadow of death, and burst their bonds apart.</em> Bonds bursting and coming out of darkness — the resurrection. Acts 2:24: <em>God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it.</em> The bonds of death burst at the resurrection; those in Christ are brought out of the shadow of death into the light of everlasting life.</p>",
    "15": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!</em> The second refrain — thanksgiving for steadfast love and wondrous works. The church's perpetual offering: <em>through him then let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God, that is, the fruit of lips that acknowledge his name</em> (Heb 13:15). The refrain of Ps 107 is the heartbeat of Christian worship.</p>",
    "16": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For he shatters the doors of bronze and cuts in two the bars of iron.</em> Shattering bronze doors and iron bars — Christ's victory over death. <em>The gates of hell shall not prevail against it</em> (Matt 16:18). Christ descends into death and shatters its doors from the inside (Acts 2:24). The bars of iron imprisoning humanity are cut apart by his resurrection power — <em>I have the keys of Death and Hades</em> (Rev 1:18).</p>",
    "17": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Some were fools through their sinful ways, and because of their iniquities suffered affliction;</em> Sickness as consequence of sin — the connection Christ complicates and ultimately resolves. While not all sickness is direct punishment (John 9:3), the root of all human suffering is the fall. Christ addresses both: he heals the sick and forgives sins (Matt 9:2-7), dealing with symptoms and cause together.</p>",
    "18": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>they loathed any kind of food, and they drew near to the gates of death.</em> Drawing near to the gates of death — the terminal condition Christ reverses. He stands outside the tomb of Lazarus and proclaims: <em>I am the resurrection and the life. Whoever believes in me, though he die, yet shall he live</em> (John 11:25). Those at the gates of death find in Christ the one who holds the keys of death and Hades (Rev 1:18).</p>",
    "19": "<p><span class=\"level\">type</span> <em>Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress.</em> The third rescue refrain — cry answered by deliverance. The pattern encoded in the Lord's Prayer: <em>deliver us from evil</em> (Matt 6:13). Christ teaches his disciples to cry to the Father in distress because he has demonstrated that such cries are heard — his own cry received the ultimate answer in resurrection.</p>",
    "20": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>He sent out his word and healed them, and delivered them from their destruction.</em> God sending his word to heal — the Incarnation as the supreme sending of the Word. John 1:14: <em>the Word became flesh and dwelt among us.</em> The healing word of v20 is no longer just spoken but embodied. Christ heals with a word across distance (Matt 8:8: <em>only say the word, and my servant will be healed</em>) and into death itself.</p>",
    "21": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!</em> The third refrain — thanksgiving arising from healing and deliverance. The ten lepers are healed; one returns to thank Christ. <em>Was no one found to return and give praise to God except this foreigner?</em> (Luke 17:18). The Samaritan's return is the shape of the refrain enacted — the redeemed soul giving thanks for God's wondrous works.</p>",
    "22": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>and let them offer sacrifices of thanksgiving, and tell of his deeds in songs of joy!</em> Sacrifices of thanksgiving and songs of joy — the Christian worship pattern. Heb 13:15: <em>through him then let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God.</em> The physical sacrifices of the OT are replaced by the sacrifice of praise through Christ, and the songs of joy find their content in the deeds of the one who saved us.</p>",
    "23": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Some went down to the sea in ships, doing business on the great waters;</em> Those doing business on the great waters — the disciples Christ calls from their nets (Matt 4:18-22). He comes to those at work on the sea, calls them to follow him, and makes them fishers of men. The sea remains in view throughout his ministry — where he walks (Matt 14:25), stills storms (Matt 8:26), and provides miraculous catches (John 21:6).</p>",
    "24": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>they saw the deeds of the LORD, his wondrous works in the deep.</em> Wondrous works in the deep — the disciples witnessing Christ's sea miracles. When Jesus walks on water, those in the boat worship him: <em>Truly you are the Son of God</em> (Matt 14:33). When he calms the storm: <em>What sort of man is this, that even winds and sea obey him?</em> (Matt 8:27). The wondrous works of the LORD in the deep are the signature acts of the incarnate Son.</p>",
    "25": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For he commanded and raised the stormy wind, which lifted up the waves of the sea.</em> Commanding the storm — authority over wind and wave that belongs to Christ. Mark 4:39: <em>he rebuked the wind and said to the sea, Peace! Be still! And the wind ceased, and there was a great calm.</em> The disciples' reaction — fear and wonder — is the right response to one who commands creation with a word.</p>",
    "26": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>They mounted up to heaven; they went down to the depths; their courage melted away in their evil plight;</em> Courage melting in the storm — the disciples' terror: <em>they were filled with great fear and said to one another, Who then is this?</em> (Mark 4:41). The storm that tests courage is the occasion for Christ's identity to be revealed. Human courage that melts gives way to the peace Christ bestows: <em>Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you</em> (John 14:27).</p>",
    "27": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>they reeled and staggered like drunken men and were at their wits' end.</em> At their wits' end — the desperate condition that drives people to Christ. Peter begins to sink and cries: <em>Lord, save me!</em> (Matt 14:30). The cry of a man out of all human options is the cry Christ answers immediately — <em>Jesus immediately reached out his hand and took hold of him.</em></p>",
    "28": "<p><span class=\"level\">type</span> <em>Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress.</em> The fourth rescue refrain — enacted in the storm on Galilee. Each refrain of Ps 107 is embodied in the Gospels: wanderers found (v7), prisoners released (v14), sick healed (v20), sailors rescued (v28-30). Christ is the LORD of Ps 107 performing all four deliverances in person.</p>",
    "29": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>He made the storm be still, and the waves of the sea were hushed.</em> The stilled storm — Mark 4:39: the storm becomes still at Christ's word. This is the direct enactment of Ps 107:29 in his ministry: the LORD who stills storms in the psalm stills them in person through the human Jesus. The hushed waves testify that this man is God.</p>",
    "30": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Then they were glad that the waters were quiet, and he brought them to their desired haven.</em> Brought to the desired haven — the rest Christ provides. <em>Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest</em> (Matt 11:28). The desired haven is ultimately the Father's house: <em>I go to prepare a place for you</em> (John 14:2). Christ pilots every storm-battered soul to the haven of eternal rest.</p>",
    "31": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!</em> The fourth and final refrain — the crescendo of thanksgiving. Rev 7:9-12: the great multitude from every nation stands before the Lamb and cries: <em>Salvation belongs to our God who sits on the throne, and to the Lamb!</em> — the eschatological fulfillment of the Ps 107 refrain as all the redeemed thank the LORD for his steadfast love and wondrous works in Christ.</p>",
    "32": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Let them extol him in the congregation of the people, and praise him in the assembly of the elders.</em> Praise in the congregation — Heb 2:12 applies Ps 22:22 to Christ: <em>in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise</em> — Christ himself praising the Father in the gathered church. He is the lead worshiper, the firstborn among many brothers (Rom 8:29), praising the Father in the assembly of his people.</p>",
    "33": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He turns rivers into a desert, springs of water into thirsty ground,</em> Rivers turned to desert — the judgment side of God's sovereignty. Christ pronounces judgment over unrepentant cities (Matt 11:20-24): greater works were done there than in Tyre and Sidon, but they did not repent. The rivers of blessing become the desert of judgment when the one who came to save is rejected.</p>",
    "34": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>a fruitful land into a salty waste, because of the evil of its inhabitants.</em> Fruitful land made barren — the cursing of the fig tree (Mark 11:13-14) enacts this: the fruitless tree that should bear becomes permanently fruitless. The fruitful land made salt is the Israel that rejected its Messiah; the judgment of 70 AD (Matt 24:2) is the historical embodiment of this principle.</p>",
    "35": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He turns a desert into pools of water, a parched land into springs of water.</em> Desert turned into pools — the new creation. Rev 21:6: <em>to the thirsty I will give from the spring of the water of life without payment.</em> Isa 35:6-7 (streams in the desert) is cited in connection with Christ's healings (Matt 11:5). The desert turned to pools is the eschatological restoration Christ inaugurates.</p>",
    "36": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>And there he lets the hungry dwell, and they establish a city to live in;</em> The hungry established in a city — the Beatitudes' hungry and thirsty gathered into the kingdom (Matt 5:3-6). The city they establish is the New Jerusalem: <em>I saw the holy city, new Jerusalem, coming down out of heaven from God</em> (Rev 21:2). The once-wandering hungry now dwell in the eternal city.</p>",
    "37": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>they sow fields and plant vineyards and get a fruitful yield.</em> Sowing, planting, fruitful yield — the kingdom parables. The sower (Matt 13:3-9), the vineyard (John 15:1-8), the harvest (John 4:35-38). Christ plants his disciples in him as branches to bear much fruit. The fruitful yield of v37 is the harvest of the new creation — fruit that abides forever (John 15:16).</p>",
    "38": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>By his blessing they multiply greatly, and he does not let their livestock diminish.</em> Multiplication by divine blessing — the growth of the church. Acts 6:7: <em>the number of the disciples multiplied greatly in Jerusalem.</em> The fruitful multiplication of v38 is the church's growth through the word of Christ, multiplying in every nation under heaven.</p>",
    "39": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>When they are diminished and brought low through oppression, evil, and sorrow,</em> Diminished through oppression — the suffering of the church participating in Christ's pattern. <em>We are afflicted in every way, but not crushed... struck down, but not destroyed</em> (2 Cor 4:8-9). The diminishment of v39 leads to the reversal of v41 — the pattern of cross and resurrection that defines Christian existence.</p>",
    "40": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>he pours contempt on princes and makes them wander in trackless wastes;</em> Contempt on princes — the reversal of the powerful. Mary's Magnificat: <em>he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate</em> (Luke 1:52). The cross is the supreme enactment: the princes of this age condemned the Lord of glory (1 Cor 2:8), but God exalted the crucified one above every name (Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "41": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>but he raises up the needy out of affliction and makes their families like flocks.</em> The needy raised from affliction — <em>blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven</em> (Matt 5:3). Christ's resurrection is the paradigm: the one crucified in weakness is raised in power (2 Cor 13:4). Those in him share the same trajectory: through affliction into glory (Rom 8:17-18).</p>",
    "42": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>The upright see it and are glad, and all wickedness shuts its mouth.</em> Wickedness shutting its mouth — Rom 3:19: <em>every mouth may be stopped and the whole world may be held accountable to God.</em> At the final judgment every mouth is stopped before the righteousness of God revealed in Christ (Rom 3:21-26). The upright who see the vindication of Christ are glad with permanent joy.</p>",
    "43": "<p><span class=\"level\">revelation of God</span> <em>Whoever is wise, let him attend to these things; let them consider the steadfast love of the LORD.</em> Wisdom attending to God's steadfast love — Christ is the wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:24); considering his steadfast love is the highest wisdom. <em>In him are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge</em> (Col 2:3). The wise person of Ps 107's close is the one who sees in Christ the full disclosure of the steadfast love that endures forever.</p>",
  },
  "108": {
    "1": "<p><span class=\"level\">theme</span> <em>My heart is steadfast, O God! I will sing and make melody with all my being!</em> Singing with all one's being — the wholehearted praise Christ models as the lead worshiper in the congregation (Heb 2:12; Ps 22:22). Phil 4:4: <em>Rejoice in the Lord always; again I will say, rejoice.</em> The steadfast heart is the heart kept by the peace of God (Phil 4:7); the whole-being melody is the worship Christ enables and joins.</p>",
    "2": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Awake, O harp and lyre! I will awake the dawn!</em> Awakening the dawn with praise — the resurrection morning. Christ is raised at dawn (Luke 24:1 — <em>on the first day of the week, at early dawn</em>), his resurrection awakening a new dawn for all creation. The harps find their eschatological fulfillment in Rev 5:8: the four living creatures and elders hold harps and sing to the Lamb.</p>",
    "3": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>I will give thanks to you, O Lord, among the peoples; I will sing praises to you among the nations.</em> Rom 15:9 includes this verse in Paul's catena supporting Gentile praise: <em>Therefore I will praise you among the Gentiles, and sing to your name.</em> The psalmist's resolve to praise among the nations is fulfilled in Christ's mission (Matt 28:19) and Paul's apostolate — the whole world now sings praises to the LORD through Christ.</p>",
    "4": "<p><span class=\"level\">revelation of God</span> <em>For your steadfast love is great above the heavens; your faithfulness reaches to the clouds.</em> Love above the heavens and faithfulness to the clouds — the immeasurable love Paul reaches for in Eph 3:18-19: <em>that you may have strength to comprehend... what is the breadth and length and height and depth, and to know the love of Christ that surpasses knowledge.</em> The love that exceeds the heavens is the love of God revealed in Christ.</p>",
    "5": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>Be exalted, O God, above the heavens! Let your glory be over all the earth!</em> God exalted above the heavens — fulfilled in Christ's exaltation: <em>God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name</em> (Phil 2:9). His glory covers the earth: <em>the earth will be filled with the knowledge of the glory of the LORD as the waters cover the sea</em> (Hab 2:14). The prayer of v5 is answered in the exaltation of the Son.</p>",
    "6": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>That your beloved may be delivered, give salvation by your right hand and answer me!</em> The beloved delivered by God's right hand — Christ the beloved Son: <em>This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased</em> (Matt 3:17). The beloved is delivered by the Father's right hand through resurrection (Acts 2:33: <em>exalted at the right hand of God</em>). Those in the beloved receive the same deliverance (Eph 1:6).</p>",
    "7": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>God has promised in his holiness: \"With exultation I will divide up Shechem and portion out the Vale of Succoth.</em> God dividing the land in holy promise — the land of Canaan was the type; the inheritance Christ secures is the new heavens and new earth (Rev 21:1). Heb 11:10: the patriarchs looked for a city whose builder and maker is God. God's holy promise of the land finds its ultimate fulfillment in the eternal inheritance (1 Pet 1:4).</p>",
    "8": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Gilead is mine; Manasseh is mine; Ephraim is my helmet; Judah is my scepter.</em> Judah as God's scepter — Gen 49:10: <em>the scepter shall not depart from Judah... until tribute comes to him.</em> Christ, of the tribe of Judah (Heb 7:14; Rev 5:5 — <em>the Lion of the tribe of Judah</em>), is the fulfillment of the Judah-scepter: the ruler from Judah to whom the nations belong.</p>",
    "9": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Moab is my washbasin; upon Edom I cast my shoe; over Philistia I shout in triumph.</em> The surrounding nations subdued — the universal lordship of Christ. Rev 17:14: <em>the Lamb will conquer them, for he is Lord of lords and King of kings.</em> The enemies of Israel are types of the spiritual forces Christ overcomes at the cross: <em>he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him</em> (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "10": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Who will bring me to the fortified city? Who will lead me to Edom?</em> Asking who will lead to the fortified city — the question Christ answers. He is the way to the city no human strategy can reach (John 14:6). The forerunner who enters the inner place behind the curtain on our behalf (Heb 6:19-20) is the one who brings us to the fortified city no army can take by force.</p>",
    "11": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Have you not rejected us, O God? You do not go out, O God, with our armies.</em> God seeming to abandon — the darkness of Gethsemane and Golgotha. Christ enters the experience of divine absence: <em>My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?</em> (Matt 27:46) — so that God will never truly abandon those who are in him (Heb 13:5: <em>I will never leave you nor forsake you</em>). His cry purchased the promise of perpetual presence.</p>",
    "12": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Oh grant us help against the foe, for vain is the salvation of man.</em> Human salvation is vain — the inadequacy of all human help drives the necessity of divine rescue. <em>Salvation belongs to the LORD</em> (Jonah 2:9). No human effort reaches the depth of need; only the divine-human Savior is sufficient. Acts 4:12: <em>there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved.</em></p>",
    "13": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>With God we shall do valiantly; it is he who will tread down our foes.</em> Valor and victory through God — the confidence of Rom 8:37: <em>in all these things we are more than conquerors through him who loved us.</em> The courage to do valiantly is not human bravado but faith in the one who has already trodden down the ultimate foe: <em>the last enemy to be destroyed is death</em> (1 Cor 15:26), and Christ destroys it in his resurrection.</p>",
  },
  "109": {
    "1": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Be not silent, O God of my praise!</em> Calling on God not to be silent in the face of accusation — the prayer Christ implicitly prays in his sufferings. The Father answers by raising him: <em>The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone; this is the Lord's doing, and it is marvelous in our eyes</em> (Ps 118:22-23; Matt 21:42). The resurrection is God refusing to be silent about his Son.</p>",
    "2": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For wicked and deceitful mouths are opened against me, speaking against me with lying tongues.</em> Wicked and deceitful mouths — the false witnesses at Jesus's trial: <em>the chief priests and the whole council were seeking false testimony against Jesus that they might put him to death, but they found none, though many false witnesses came forward</em> (Matt 26:59-60). The lying tongues of v2 opened against innocent David are opened against innocent Christ in the Sanhedrin's midnight court.</p>",
    "3": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>They encircle me with words of hate, and attack me without cause.</em> Attacked without cause — John 15:25: <em>they hated me without a cause.</em> The encirclement with hate is the arrest in Gethsemane, the ring of soldiers, the mob crying <em>crucify him!</em> The causeless attack on the innocent becomes the ground of his atoning work: he who was hated without cause bore the hatred we deserved.</p>",
    "4": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>In return for my love they accuse me, but I give myself to prayer.</em> Love repaid with accusation, responded to with prayer — Christ at the cross: <em>Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do</em> (Luke 23:34). Love given and rejected; prayer offered for the accusers. Heb 7:25: <em>he always lives to make intercession for them.</em> Even now, Christ gives himself to prayer — interceding for those who once accused him.</p>",
    "5": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>So they reward me evil for good, and hatred for my love.</em> Evil for good and hatred for love — the moral inversion of the crucifixion. Christ gives every good thing and receives in return betrayal, accusation, death. <em>He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him</em> (John 1:11). The reward of hatred for love becomes the occasion for the greatest act of love: giving his life for those who hated him (Rom 5:10).</p>",
    "6": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Appoint a wicked man against him; let an accuser stand at his right hand.</em> Accuser at the right hand — the courtroom imagery reversed in Christ. The accuser (Satan = the accuser; Rev 12:10) who stands against humanity is defeated at the cross. Christ stands as our advocate: <em>if anyone does sin, we have an advocate with the Father, Jesus Christ the righteous</em> (1 John 2:1). He has taken the accusation so that the accuser has nothing left to say against those in him (Rom 8:33).</p>",
    "7": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>When he is tried, let him come forth guilty; let his prayer be counted as sin!</em> Prayer counted as sin — the grotesque judgment the court rendered on Christ: his claims were treated as blasphemy deserving death (Matt 26:65). The innocent one was found guilty. But God reversed the verdict: the resurrection is the Father's judgment that Christ is righteous (1 Tim 3:16: <em>vindicated by the Spirit</em>).</p>",
    "8": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>May his days be few; may another take his office!</em> Acts 1:20: Peter explicitly quotes this verse when explaining the need to replace Judas: <em>His office let another take.</em> The betrayer of the innocent — Judas, who handed over the suffering servant — fulfills the imprecation of v8. The selection of Matthias (Acts 1:26) is the direct fulfillment of \"let another take his office\" — the apostolic vacancy created by betrayal is filled by divine appointment.</p>",
    "9": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May his children be fatherless and his wife a widow!</em> The consequences falling on the betrayer's household — historically fulfilled in Judas's death (Acts 1:18) and the desolation of his household. Judas's judgment is not a contradiction of the gospel but its confirmation: the one who hands over the holy Son of God receives the death he facilitated.</p>",
    "10": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May his children wander about and beg, seeking food far from the ruins they inhabit!</em> Children wandering and begging — the consequences of betrayal. The contrast is with Christ's promise: <em>I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you</em> (John 14:18). Those who betray Christ are left fatherless; those who follow him receive the Spirit of adoption crying <em>Abba, Father!</em> (Rom 8:15).</p>",
    "11": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May the creditor seize all that he has; may strangers plunder the fruits of his toil!</em> Creditors seizing everything — Judas received thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:15), threw them into the temple (Matt 27:5), and the money was used to buy the potter's field (Matt 27:7). The wages of betrayal became property of strangers — providential irony: the betrayer's payment purchased the field of his burial.</p>",
    "12": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Let there be none to extend kindness to him, nor anyone to pity his fatherless children!</em> No kindness extended — the stark end of one who showed no mercy in betraying the innocent. The contrast with Christ: even on the cross he shows kindness to the thief beside him (<em>today you will be with me in paradise</em>, Luke 23:43) and provides for his mother (John 19:26-27). The absence of mercy toward the betrayer makes Christ's mercy shine more brightly.</p>",
    "13": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May his posterity be cut off; may his name be blotted out in the second generation!</em> Name blotted out — the anti-Deuteronomic judgment: rather than a name remembered for generations (Prov 10:7), the betrayer's name is cut off. Rev 3:5: Christ promises to those who overcome that <em>I will never blot his name out of the book of life.</em> Those faithful to Christ have their names written; those who betray him face erasure.</p>",
    "14": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May the iniquity of his fathers be remembered before the LORD, and let not the sin of his mother be blotted out.</em> Ancestral iniquity remembered — the gravity of covenant betrayal reaching back through generations. The cross settles all such ancestral accounts for those who are in Christ: <em>canceling the record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands. This he set aside, nailing it to the cross</em> (Col 2:13-14). The betrayer's debt is left uncanceled; the believer's is nailed to the cross.</p>",
    "15": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Let them be before the LORD continually, that he may cut off the memory of them from the earth!</em> Memory cut off — the permanent erasure of the unfaithful. In contrast, Christ is the one whose memory is perpetually proclaimed: <em>do this in remembrance of me</em> (1 Cor 11:24-25). The church's Eucharistic remembrance keeps alive the name and work of the one the betrayer tried to silence.</p>",
    "16": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For he did not remember to show kindness, but pursued the poor and needy and the brokenhearted, to put them to death.</em> Not showing kindness — the indictment of those who oppose the poor and brokenhearted. Christ identifies himself with them: <em>the Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor... to bind up the brokenhearted</em> (Luke 4:18; Isa 61:1). To pursue the poor and brokenhearted is to pursue Christ (Matt 25:45).</p>",
    "17": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He loved to curse; let curses come upon him! He did not delight in blessing; may it be far from him!</em> The one who loved cursing receiving curses — Gal 6:7: <em>God is not mocked, for whatever one sows, that will he also reap.</em> But Christ voluntarily absorbed the curse that falls on the guilty: <em>Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us</em> (Gal 3:13). The curse earned by treachery was borne by the innocent — so that those in him receive blessing instead.</p>",
    "18": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He clothed himself with cursing as his coat; may it soak into his body like water, like oil into his bones!</em> Cursing soaking in like oil — the perversion of the priestly anointing (Ps 133:2). Rather than sacred oil of blessing, it is the oil of self-inflicted curse. The contrast with Christ the Anointed (Messiah) who became a curse to break the curse (Gal 3:13) — the true anointing brings blessing where treachery brought cursing.</p>",
    "19": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May it be like a garment that he wraps around him, like a belt that he puts on every day!</em> Cursing worn daily like a garment — the inescapable consequence of betraying the innocent. The garment imagery recalls Christ's garments divided at the cross (John 19:23-24), and the robe of righteousness he gives to those who follow him (Rev 19:8). The betrayer wraps himself in cursing; the believer is clothed with Christ (Gal 3:27).</p>",
    "20": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May this be the reward of my accusers from the LORD, of those who speak evil against my life!</em> The reward of accusers — the eschatological judgment. Rev 20:12-15: the books are opened; those whose names are not in the book of life face the lake of fire. But Christ prays for his accusers (Luke 23:34) — his intercession delays and in many cases transforms the reward, converting accusers into worshipers.</p>",
    "21": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>But you, O GOD my Lord, deal on my behalf for your name's sake; because your steadfast love is good, deliver me!</em> Calling on God's name and steadfast love for deliverance — the prayer Christ prays in Gethsemane: <em>Father, if you are willing, remove this cup from me. Nevertheless, not my will, but yours, be done</em> (Luke 22:42). The appeal to God's steadfast love is the appeal of the innocent sufferer who trusts the Father through the darkest hour.</p>",
    "22": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For I am poor and needy, and my heart is stricken within me.</em> Poor, needy, heart stricken — Christ's Gethsemane condition: <em>my soul is very sorrowful, even to death</em> (Matt 26:38). He who was rich became poor (2 Cor 8:9); he who was Lord of all entered the depths of human need and anguish. He entered this poverty voluntarily so that through his poverty we might become rich (2 Cor 8:9).</p>",
    "23": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>I am gone like a shadow at evening; I am shaken off like a locust.</em> Like a fading shadow — the mortal vulnerability of the suffering one. Christ's mortality was real: he was genuinely subject to death (Heb 2:14 — <em>he himself likewise partook of flesh and blood... that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death</em>). He submitted to the evening shadow of mortality so that death could not hold him and those in him escape its power.</p>",
    "24": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>My knees are weak through fasting; my body has become gaunt, with no fat.</em> Weakness through fasting — Christ's forty-day fast in the wilderness (Matt 4:2: <em>afterward he was hungry</em>). He entered genuine physical weakness — not docetic strength disguised as weakness but actual bodily diminishment. In that weakened state he refused to turn stones to bread, trusting God's provision over physical need (Matt 4:4).</p>",
    "25": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>I am an object of scorn to my accusers; when they see me, they wag their heads.</em> Matt 27:39 fulfills this directly: <em>those who passed by derided him, wagging their heads and saying, You who would destroy the temple and rebuild it in three days, save yourself!</em> The very gesture of contempt — the head-wag of the scornful — is specifically enacted at the crucifixion, marking the scene as fulfillment of the suffering servant's experience in Ps 109.</p>",
    "26": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Help me, O LORD my God! Save me according to your steadfast love!</em> The cry for salvation by steadfast love — answered in the resurrection. <em>He was heard because of his reverence</em> (Heb 5:7). The Father's steadfast love answers Christ's prayer by raising him from the dead; the resurrection is God's <em>yes</em> to the prayer of his Son. Those who cry the same prayer are heard in Christ's name.</p>",
    "27": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Let them know that this is your hand; you, O LORD, have done it!</em> God's hand doing it — the disciples recognizing the resurrection as God's act. Acts 2:24: <em>God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death;</em> Acts 2:36: <em>let all the house of Israel therefore know for certain that God has made him both Lord and Christ, this Jesus whom you crucified.</em> The knowledge that this is God's hand is the content of the Pentecost proclamation.</p>",
    "28": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>They may curse, but you will bless; when they arise, they will be put to shame, but your servant will be glad!</em> They curse, God blesses — the resurrection reversal. The accusers of the cross thought they had ended the story with a curse; God blessed by raising the crucified one. <em>He is not here; he has risen</em> (Matt 28:6). The servants of the crucified Lord are glad because the one they serve is vindicated — and their gladness is permanent: <em>no one will take your joy from you</em> (John 16:22).</p>",
    "29": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>May my accusers be clothed with dishonor; may they be wrapped in their own shame as in a cloak!</em> Accusers clothed with dishonor — the eschatological reversal of the cross. The soldiers clothed Jesus in a purple robe of mockery (John 19:2-3). At his return, the mocked becomes the glorified: <em>behold, he is coming with the clouds, and every eye will see him, even those who pierced him</em> (Rev 1:7). The mockers face the one they clothed in shame.</p>",
    "30": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>With my mouth I will give great thanks to the LORD; I will praise him in the midst of the throng.</em> Praising in the midst of the throng — Heb 2:12 applies Ps 22:22 to Christ: <em>in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise.</em> The risen Christ praises the Father in the midst of the church. The thanksgiving of v30 is Christ's post-resurrection praise in the assembly of his disciples, in which all believers are caught up.</p>",
    "31": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>For he stands at the right hand of the needy one, to save him from those who condemn his soul to death.</em> Standing at the right hand of the needy — the intercession of Christ. Rom 8:34: <em>Christ Jesus is the one who died — more than that, who was raised — who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us.</em> The one who was himself condemned now stands as advocate for all who are condemned. The needy of Ps 109 find Christ at their right hand.</p>",
  },
  "110": {
    "2": "<p><span class=\"level\">direct</span> <em>The LORD sends forth your mighty scepter from Zion. Rule in the midst of your enemies!</em> The ruling scepter sent from Zion — Christ's current reign from his heavenly enthronement. Acts 2:33-36: God has made Jesus both Lord and Christ, seated at his right hand. <em>All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me</em> (Matt 28:18). He rules now, in the midst of enemies, through the church's proclamation and the Spirit's power — the mission of Matt 28:19 is the exercise of this scepter.</p>",
    "3": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>Your people will offer themselves freely on the day of your power, in holy garments; from the womb of the morning, the dew of your youth will be like dew.</em> Freely offered, holy-garmented people on the day of power — the church gathered by the Spirit at Pentecost. <em>God is at work in you, both to will and to work for his good pleasure</em> (Phil 2:13). Holy garments: clothed with Christ (Gal 3:27). The dew of youth: the inexhaustible vitality of Christ's eternal priesthood, the endless spring of the new covenant people.</p>",
    "5": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>The Lord is at your right hand; he will shatter kings on the day of his wrath.</em> Shattering kings on the day of wrath — Rev 19:11-16: the rider on the white horse, with a name written King of kings and Lord of lords, strikes down the nations. The day of Christ's wrath is the day of his return; the kings who resisted his rule face the scepter that shatters (Ps 2:9: <em>you shall break them with a rod of iron, and dash them in pieces like a potter's vessel</em>).</p>",
    "6": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He will execute judgment among the nations, filling them with corpses; he will shatter chiefs over the wide earth.</em> Judgment executed among the nations — the final judgment of Rev 20:11-15 and Rev 19:17-21. Matt 25:31-46: all nations gathered before the Son of Man; he separates the sheep from the goats, executing judgment across the wide earth. The one who came first in humility comes again in the fullness of this authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p><span class=\"level\">shadow</span> <em>He will drink from the brook by the way; therefore he will lift up his head.</em> Drinking from the brook and lifting up the head — the humiliation and exaltation of Christ. The warrior-king pauses to drink (condescension into mortality); then lifts his head in victory. Christ took the cup of suffering (Matt 26:42: <em>let this cup not pass from me</em>), drank it fully on the cross, and was exalted: <em>Therefore God has highly exalted him</em> (Phil 2:9). Heb 12:2: <em>who for the joy set before him endured the cross... and is seated at the right hand of the throne of God.</em></p>",
  }
}


if __name__ == "__main__":
    book = "psalms"
    source = "mkt-christ"
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
